Preliminary Wrangling¶

This dataset reports flights in the United States, including carriers, arrival and departure delays, and reasons for delays, from 1987 to 2008. The data comes originally from RITA where it is described in detail. These files have derivable variables removed, are packaged in yearly chunks and have been more heavily compressed than the originals.

In total, 23 csv files have been downloaded, decompressed and marged during this study. The process of combining those files took around (6.4) mins to generate a giant DataFrame called [df_flights] that has [123,534,969] entries (rows) each with [29] variables (columns). This dataframe will be used during the wrangling and analyzing process.

proc_time = time.time()

# Save all flights csv files as a list:   
all_flights = [file for file in glob.glob('Flighs Data/csv/*.csv')]

df_flights = pd.concat([pd.read_csv(file, encoding ='ISO-8859-1') for file in all_flights ])

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This giant DataFrame has [123,534,969] entries (rows) each with [29] variables (columns).

# Variable descriptions s|Name | Description --- | :-: | :-: 1|Year | 1987-2008 2|Month | 1-12 3|DayofMonth|1-31 4|DayOfWeek|1 (Monday) - 7 (Sunday) 5|DepTime|actual departure time (local, hhmm) 6|CRSDepTime|scheduled departure time (local, hhmm) 7|ArrTime|actual arrival time (local, hhmm) 8|CRSArrTime|scheduled arrival time (local, hhmm) 9|UniqueCarrier|unique carrier code 10|FlightNum|flight number 11|TailNum|plane tail number 12|ActualElapsedTime|in minutes 13|CRSElapsedTime|in minutes 14|AirTime|in minutes 15|ArrDelay|arrival delay, in minutes 16|DepDelay|departure delay, in minutes 17|Origin|origin IATA airport code 18|Dest|destination IATA airport code 19|Distance|in miles 20|TaxiIn|taxi in time, in minutes 21|TaxiOut|taxi out time in minutes 22|Cancelled|was the flight cancelled? 23|CancellationCode|reason for cancellation (A = carrier, B = weather, C = NAS, D = security) 24|Diverted|1 = yes, 0 = no 25|CarrierDelay|in minutes 26|WeatherDelay|in minutes 27|NASDelay|in minutes 28|SecurityDelay|in minutes 29|LateAircraftDelay|in minutes

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  • How the total number of flights has been changed over the years?
  • Which airlines operate more flights and how this has been changed over the years?
  • Is there a relation between the number of operated flights and the total delay time?
  • What are the critical periods of the year that has the most recorded delays?
  • How the Departure delay is affecting the Arrival Delay?
  • How much time delayed by each delay cause? and how this is related to the number of flights?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • As the dataset has a dedicated columns that show the actual delay in minutes for both Arrival and Departure, this will be very useful to study the delay times from different aspects. This was planed to be calculated anyhow.
  • Time factors including: Year, Month and Days.
  • Delay causes.
  • Cancellation status.

Preparing data:¶

first, we need to clean the dataset by removing unrequired columns and preparing sub-dataset to speedup the processing time.

Unrequired columns are:

  • CRSDepTime
  • CRSArrTime
  • FlightNum
  • TailNum
  • ActualElapsedTime
  • CRSElapsedTime
  • AirTime
  • TaxiIn
  • TaxiOut

Things to consider:

  • Cancellation Code and Cuases were not recorded before 2002
  • TailNum, AirTime, TaxiIn, TaxiOut values were not recorded before 1994
In [13]:
# Delete unrequired columns: 
columns = ['CRSDepTime','CRSArrTime','CRSArrTime','TailNum', 'FlightNum', 'ActualElapsedTime',
           'CRSElapsedTime', 'AirTime', 'TaxiIn','TaxiOut']
df_flights.drop(columns,axis=1,inplace=True)

# Add Total_Delay column that indicate the total delay for each flight: 
df_flights.insert(9, 'total_delay', df_flights.ArrDelay + df_flights.DepDelay)

# Rename [DayofMonth] column: 
df_flights.rename(columns={'DayofMonth': 'DayOfMonth'}, inplace=True)

# Function to plot a bar graph for a given dataframe with certain formate:
def plotGraph(df, graphSize, barColor, edgeColor, a, title, xLbl, yLbl, fontSize, ylim):
    graph = df.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(graphSize, graphSize), ylim=ylim, alpha=a, color=barColor ,edgecolor=edgeColor)
    graph.set_title(title, size= fontSize) 
    graph.set_xlabel(xLbl, size = fontSize)
    graph.set_ylabel(yLbl, size = fontSize)
    graph.grid(True, which='major', color='gray', alpha=0.05);
    return graph

#1# How the total number of flights has been changed over the years?

As we can see from this general view of our flighs dataset, over the years the number of flights has been increased and it's predicted to keep increasing. Seems like the overload of the flight is generally equally distributed among the months. I was expecting to see a huge difference between summer and other months. The current difference is about 800K flights.

#2# What are the critical periods of the year that has the most recorded delays?

The graph showed that the last day of the month day 31 has the lowest number of flights, this is due to the fact that only 7 months out of 12 have 31 days. Intrestingly, Saturday has also the lowest number of flights with almost 3 million flights.

#3# Which airlines operate more flights and how this has been changed over the years?

Overview of US airlines showed that [29] carriers have been busy operating [123,534,969] over the last 23 years. As shown above, there was a jump on 1988 and this is expected due to the increase in the number of carriers and the boom in economic activity in aviation.

What really caught my eyes is what happened in 2002?! There is a slight drop in the number of flights with almost [700K] flights and some carriers, such as ("AQ","Aloha Airlines Inc.") were disappeared!! Searching the company Wiki's page attributed this to what happened in September 2001.

Above graphs show direct correlation between number of flights, delay time and cancelation rate over the years.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

As stated before, in general, over the years the number of flights increased constantly. The same applys withdelay time and cancelation rate. Except in 2002, a notible drop has been noticed and this is due an controled causes. Studying the delay time has also an interesting findings in which almost 150 flight were delayed for over a day, which reflects on the hist graph as a long tail on the right side of the graph. This required me to change the scale of the graph to be a Logarithmic scale to represent the data in a better form.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Yes, as the data was originally scattered into 23 csv files, I marged them into one large csv file (Master Dataframe) that contains all flights infor for the 23 years. Then, I cleaned the dataframe by deleting unrequired columns, calculating [total_daly] column which combined both Departure and Arraival delays, anf finally did minor name changing for [DayofMonth] column.
